rove the configuration checks, particularly around Class.forName. While it’s a common method, I realize there are limitations in how we handle failures. Using `RandomAccessInterface.class.getName()` as file access doesn’t provide a constructor. AtomicReference seems invalid as well since it covers a fallback but lacks a direct link to FileAccess. HSQL captures exceptions but might not support the required behavior. Perhaps I should split the checks into TCCL success and a fallback for robustness.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Refining class loading strategy**\\n\\nFor the parent issue, I see that TCCL success can still cover the three cases. When using Class.forName, I think we should incorporate FileUtil as a fallback. We need to edit our approach, making direct use clear without hiding. The second direct attempt could likely fail, so perhaps we should repurpose it to focus on fallback validity instead. Using `org.hsqldb.lib.FileUtil$FileAccessRes` could streamline it without requiring a DatabaseManager, particularly if we rely on a memory connection instead. Let’s test this out!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Adjusting exception handling**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how `Logger.open` catches NoSuchMethodException as a generic Exception and prints an \\\"Exception\\\" message; I guess that makes the test output acceptable. HSQL prints to stdout too, so I’m considering that. However, I don’t want to create coverage by asserting known issues. I should rename the method to \\\"openFallsBackWhenContextLoaderCannotResolveConfiguredFileAccess.\\\" But since FileAccessRes doesn’t have a constructor, maybe I should create a custom class that prioritizes TCCL success first instead.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_zgzQ0KJwAwsEtjfNpUlQLHtS|fc_050fe501af82570c016a11689f6a04819297f651d8150c9b7b", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/src/test/java/org_hsqldb/hsqldb/LoggerTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import 